    "body": "## Summary\n\nCython accepts `def f(T x not None = None)` without any error or warning for extension types T, but the default value is unreachable — calling the function without the argument triggers `TypeError` at runtime because the default violates the `not None` constraint. It would be nice for this contradictory declaration to produce a compile-time error (or at minimum a warning). The `not None` declaration is a Cython addition to normal Python syntax, so even though it is only supported on Python `def` functions, I would still expect it to be subject to Cython's compile-time checks.\n\nCython does properly catch this when using primitive types that always fail at runtime because variables of those types unequivocally do not support assignment of None.\n\n## Reproduction\n\n```cython\n# not_none_default.pyx\ncdef class Foo:\n    pass\n\ndef do_thing(Foo x not None = None):\n    print(x)\n\ndef with_str(str s not None = None):\n    print(s)\n\ndef untyped(x not None = None):\n    print(x)\n```\n\nCompile and call:\n\n```python\n>>> import not_none_default\n>>> not_none_default.do_thing()\nTypeError: Argument 'x' has incorrect type (expected not_none_default.Foo, got NoneType)\n>>> not_none_default.do_thing(None)\nTypeError: Argument 'x' has incorrect type (expected not_none_default.Foo, got NoneType)\n>>> not_none_default.do_thing(not_none_default.Foo())  # valid explicit argument\n<not_none_default.Foo object at ...>\n>>> not_none_default.with_str()\nTypeError: Argument 's' has incorrect type (expected str, got NoneType)\n>>> not_none_default.untyped()\nTypeError: Argument 'x' must not be None\n```\n\nThe function compiles, but the parameter is effectively required — the `= None` default can never satisfy the `not None` constraint. The declaration is contradictory and the default value is unreachable.\n\nThe int case fails to compile as expected\n```cython\n# not_none_default_int.pyx\ndef with_int(int x not None = None):\n    print(x)\n```\n\n## Expected behavior\n\nCython should emit a compile-time error when a parameter is declared with both `not None` and a default value of `None`, since the default can never be used without raising `TypeError`.\n\nProposed error message:\n\n```\nParameter 'x' is declared 'not None' but has a default value of None\n```\n\nAlternatively, if there's a use case for this pattern that I'm not seeing (e.g., documentation of intent for subclasses), a warning would be acceptable — but it would be nice for it to not pass silently.\n\n## Environment\n\n- Cython 3.2.5\n- Python 3.13\n- Linux x86_64\n",
